The paper discusses a framework similar to deep convolutional neural networks (DCNNs) and focuses on the analysis of the activation function and its ability to recover activation paths through the layers. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses technical innovations related to tensor sparsity and thresholding, which suggests that it may also belong to the information theory (cs.IT), numerical analysis (cs.NA), and signal processing (cs.SI) sub-categories.
